column8: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen. Posts include statuses, photos, links, videos and more. (Unique Users)
column9: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen through unpaid distribution. (Unique Users)
column10: Lifetime: The number of people who had your Page's post enter their screen through paid distribution such as an ad. (Unique Users)
column11: Lifetime: The number of times your Page's post entered a person's screen. Posts include statuses, photos, links, videos and more. (Total Count)
column12: Lifetime: The number of times your Page's posts entered a person's screen through unpaid distribution. (Total Count)
column13: Lifetime: The number of times your Page's post entered a person's screen through paid distribution such as an ad. (Total Count)
column14: Lifetime: The number of unique people who engaged in certain ways with your Page post, for example by commenting on, liking, sharing, or clicking upon particular elements of the post. (Unique Users)
column15: Lifetime: The number of people who matched the audience targeting that clicked anywhere in your post on News Feed. (Unique Users)
column16: Lifetime: The number of clicks anywhere in your post on News Feed from the user that matched the audience targeting on it. (Total Count)
column17: Lifetime: The number of people who have given negative feedback to your post. (Unique Users)
column18: Lifetime: The number of times people have given negative feedback to your post. (Total Count)
column19: Lifetime: The number of impressions of your Page post to people who have liked your Page. (Total Count)
column20: Lifetime: The number of people who saw your Page post because they've liked your Page (Unique Users)
column21: Lifetime: The number of paid impressions of your Page post to people who have liked your Page. (Total Count)
column22: Lifetime: The number of people who like your Page and who saw your Page post in an ad or sponsored story. (Unique Users)
column23: Lifetime: The number of people who have liked your Page and clicked anywhere in your posts. (Unique Users)
column24: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length without any paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column25: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length without any paid promotion. (Total Count)
column26: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length after paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column27: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed to 95% of its length after paid promotion. (Total Count)
column28: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed for more than 3 seconds without any paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column29: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed for more than 3 seconds without any paid promotion. (Total Count)
column30: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed more than 3 seconds after paid promotion. (Unique Users)
column31: Lifetime: Number of times your video was viewed more than 3 seconds after paid promotion. (Total Count)
column32: Lifetime: Average time video viewed (Total Count)
column33: Lifetime: Length of a video post (Total Count)

column2: Congratulations to the winners of the first online contest this semester! All the entries we received showcased innovation, creativity & amazing gameplay but top 3 winners had to be chosen based on the votes of our general members & judges. The competition was close & all projects were amazing! Those who couldn't make it this time should keep on making more games! Winners will receive certificates after the break & their games will also be showcased on our youtube channel very soon! Enjoy the break while you have it because AUST IDC is coming with more stunning stuff in the following weeks!

Hey IDCians! We are here with our first online competition of the season, Game Showcasing contest! Find all the information on the pic attached.  Where it's happening: *AUST IDC facebook group* : goo.gl/yjDbN1  *Registration Link*: goo.gl/efJRdw  **Judging Criteria: 60% by likes on video posted by us + 40% by judges**  Rules: Submit the google form once you are ready with the shareable google drive link of your gameplay video. Team members may consist of 1-4 max.  All general members of AUST IDC will be judging your videos through the like button.  *Demo of a gameplay video*: goo.gl/SUQXcL  Submission Deadline: Wednesday, 13-06-2018 Platform: PC,Android,Web based game. Can be anything! So, what are you waiting for? Get ready to share your very own game project even if you know it sucks! And even if you don't have any projects in hand right now, get motivated to make an awesome game this mid break. Why? Because its fun!

Attention IDC'ians Tired of holidays?Need a platform to showcase your talents? We are bringing you a series of online based competitions. First up : Game showcasing. Make a video of your developed game in no more than 4 minutes and add a description with it. Use any free video capture software online. Here is a demonstration of how to make your video featuring our Excom member Shamit Ahmed, Sofia Neherin & their friends Salman Arefin Rayen, Shammy Shanta, Masud Rana with their game "Amar Bondhu Rashed". Video editing credit goes to our very own Saif Mugdho. Rules,regulations,deadlines,prizes,procedures for video will be uploaded in the group tomorrow.The competition will start and end this week.So get ready to showcase your game no matter how much you think it sucks!

Wishing you a happy new year <3   #AUSTIDC #Wheremindscollide

We are delighted to announce that AUST  Innovation and Design Club,AUST has made an international collaboration with Cognizance, IIT Roorkeee,India for the events Mindsparks'18 and Cognizance'19. As part of the collaboration, winners of 3 segments(will be mentioned later) of Mindsparks'18 will be going to India to participate in Cognizance'19 held in march, all expenses paid for four days including accomodation and competition registration cost(except travelling cost to India) and all certificates to all winners and participants will be given by both AUST and Cognizance. This maybe the first time in the history of both countries that two national events merge on an international scale. We want to thank the whole IDC team for making this MoU possible!   For the participants of Mindsparks,this is big!  Get down with your projects,ideas and don't miss the opportunity. A massive prize money for the regional round here to be announced soon too.We request you to just wait a little more. Mindsparks'18 is going international ladies and  gentleman.   #Mindsparks'18 #Cognizance'19 #AUSTIDC #WhereMindsCollide

Since it's inception Aust Innovation and design Club had a strong goal of providing the stars of our country into the limelight of national and international stages, helping them in excelling in their endeavours. The journey of Mindsparks'19 started back in July 2018 when a bunch of enthusiasts and their mentors decided to take the club to a new height. We had no idea that such a prestigious institution such as IIT Roorkee of India would be collaborating with us to take things to the epitome of international levels and we are thankful to the organisers of cognizance, the second largest technical festival in Asia for the belief in us in spite of few hiccups. As per the memorandum between MindSparks,AUST and Cognizance, IIT Roorkee for the first time in the history of international Campus collaborations, 3 champion teams got the opportunity to take part in finals at Cognizance 19 and we are glad to let you know that out of the two teams that went to India,  1. Team Quibbler of Segment Technocad became Champions in Technocad in Cognizance 19. 2. SUST Cracker Nut/ Team Bangladesh became First runners Up in Cyborg Breaking Segment of Cognizance,19.  We thank the organisers of Cognizance for their unconditional accommodations and amazing event delivery along with welcoming Bangladesh to compete there, waving the registration and accommodation fees. We look forward to Such collabs in the future.   Cyborg Breakin team leader tonmoy says :   "This competition was the first of my international competition! I tried to give my best and succeeded by the grace of Allah. If you want to know about the event, then I would say that their event is huge! And everybody knows what they have to do to make the event successful. Central management was good, but if I talk about professionalism, then here I will keep my MindSparks ahead. Thanks so much for organizing this type of mega event in Bangladesh!"  And Technocad Champion team leader maksudul said :   প্রত্যেকের জীবনের সবথেকে বড় লক্ষ্য থাকে নিজের দেশকে কোনো না কোনোভাবে বিশ্বের সামনে তুলে ধরা। ভার্সিটি লাইফের বিগত বছরগুলোতে করা অক্লান্ত পরিশ্রমে আজকে আমাদের সেই লক্ষ্য পূরন হলো। আইআইটি গ্রাউন্ডে এসে এটুকু বুঝতে পেরেছি যে আমাদের ছেলেমেয়েরা অনেক সুযোগহীনতার মধ্যে থেকেও যে মেধা ও দক্ষতার পরিচয় দিয়ে চলেছে তা অতুলনীয়। ভারতে এসে দেখেছি রাষ্ট্র তাদের মেধাগুলোকে কিভাবে বিশ্ববিদ্যালয়গুলোতে নিরাপত্তা, স্বাধীনতা, উন্নত সুযোগ সুবিধা দিয়ে যত্ন করে পরিচর্যা করছে।   প্রচুর পরিমাণে টেকনিক্যাল প্রবলেম জয় করে এতগুলো টিমের প্রতিপক্ষে বাংলাদেশ টিমের জয় পাওয়াটা আমাদের জীবনের সেরা অর্জনের একটা হয়ে থাকবে। AUST Innovation Club কে ধন্যবাদ আমাদেরকে এই সুযোগ করে দেয়ার জন্য।  #Mindsparks19-Bangladesh #Cognizance19-India

We have an immediate need for a Public Relation and Communication Executive to join a rapidly growing team. Our rapidly-growing club needs some public relation executive who has great communication skills in both English and Bengali.   DUTIES & RESPONSIBILITIES   >Build and maintain relationships with the media and corporate world. >Secure news-based and proactive media coverage. >Manage press alias and serve as point person for inbound media opportunities. >Collaborate with the communication team to develop campaigns and tactics. >Create written content including pitches, press releases and FAQs. >Build strong cross-functional relationships with key internal partners  REQUIREMENTS   >Must be a current student of AUST(any department) >Proficient in speaking and writing English. >Excellent writing and grammar skills and professional phone presence. >Strong written and verbal communication skills. >Ability to develop strong press contacts and relationships. >Strong PC, technology, and social media skills. >Ability to positively approach challenges and committed to problem-solving. >Superb time management skills within a highly charged, fast-paced environment. >Candidate should be enthusiastic, articulate, poised, and professional >Ability to travel as required (5% of the time). AUST Innovation and Design Club updated their status.

AUST Innovation and Design Club organized for the second time, MindSparks, an inter university and college tech-biz competition, which has been one of the biggest competitions of the country. MindSparks 20 was held on the 14th and 15th of March, 2020.   The event has collaborated with Indian Institute of Technology, Roorkee, India as the previous year.   The segments of this year were: MATLAB challenge, Engineering Olympiad, Techno CAD, Truss challenge, Innovation challenge, Soccer Bot, Quad Racing, Poster Presentation and Hardware Project Showcasing. Among which the winners of Techno CAD, Quad Racing, Poster Presentation and Hardware Project Showcasing will get a chance to directly take part in Cognizance of IIT, Roorkee.   There was an additional fun segment, the Pi segment, to celebrate “Pi Day” which was on 14th March.  The program was inaugurated on the first morning by Prof. Dr. Bobby Barua, President of AUST IDC, through the flight of a drone. There were about 1200 students from 34 different universities and colleges, surpassing last year. The prize money was 280,000 Taka.  The two-day event passed with much zeal and enthusiasm of the participants, guests and visitors. MindSparks 20 ended with the closing ceremony held on the evening of 15th March, leaving many memories and a promise to come back next year.  Appreciations to our title sponsor CST, cosponsor Globe and Banglamark, food partner GoGreen, ice cream partner Igloo, photography partner Bridal Snap, news and media partner Bonik Barta and Shomokal, radio partner Jago FM and City FM, digital partner Toggle (the Daily Star), drone partner Rotor Solution, electronics partner Green Electronics and outreach partner Youth Opportunities.
MindSparks 20 has been featured in the Daily Bonik Barta ❤️

Hello to all the members of AUST IDC. Hope everybody is doing fine. Everybody is aware of the current COVID situation and the effects are doing to the different parts of the world. Among the founding members and first committee panel of AUST IDC 4 of them are currently pursuing Masters in Germany and 1 is pursuing a Masters in Australia. They are actively seeing the devastation and the dangers of this COVID virus. In those first world countries, the rates of affected people are increasing at an exponential rate. They are all following the rules of home quarantine and staying most of the time in a single room. And they all urge to all of 7943 members to try your best to stay at home without urgent works. Wash your hands with soap if there's a lack of sanitizer, try to avoid things that might make you catch a cold, drink warm waters/drinks, if you are going out using public transport you can wear one time gloves while in the transport. Don't go for fun as the educational institute is closed and you are bored. The students living abroad are staying in their room alone for the last 2 weeks if you feel bored and want to go out please consider them that they are living alone without any family members. In this quarantine time period, we hope you spend time with your family members and loved ones. We all hope if you follow simple rules the rate can be lowered. If you think you are young and the risks are low for you still we will ask you to look who is in your home. Think while you have the time. May Allah help us all and keep you and your family safe. #stay_safe

রহস্যে ঘেরা পাই!  পাই একটি ধ্রুবক সংখ্যা, বৃত্তের পরিধিকে এর ব্যাস দিয়ে ভাগ করলে পাই এর মান পাওয়া যায়। এর মান ৩.১৪১৬ । পাই একটি মূলদ সংখ্যা হওয়ায় এর মান দশমিকের পর কখনো শেষ হয় না। এতটুকু তথ্য আমরা হয়তো সকলেই জানি।  কিন্তু কিছু লোক আছে যারা এতটুকুতে ক্ষান্ত নয়, তারা (π) এর মান মুখস্ত বলাকে বিশ্ব রেকর্ডের পর্যায়ে নিয়ে গেছে। এর মধ্যে স্বীকৃত পাইয়ের মান বলার রেকর্ড হলো দশমিক এর পর ৬৭,৮৯০ ঘর, যার অধিকারী চীনের ২৪ বছর বয়স্ক স্নাতক ছাত্র লু চাও।  বাংলাদেশেও এর ব্যতিক্রম নয়, আমাদের সকলের কাছে "অংক ভাইয়া" নামে পরিচিত বুয়েটের চমক ভাইও পাই এর মান দশমিক এর পর প্রায় ৫০০ ঘরের মতো বলতে পারে।  এমনকি পাই (π) এর মান 3.14 বলে প্রতি বছর মার্চের ১৪ তারিখ পাই দিবস উদযাপন করা হয়।  AUST IDC এর উদ্যোগে এমনই এক আকর্ষণীয় সেগমেন্ট থাকছে MINDSPARKS20 এর এবারের আয়োজনে।  "পাই গেমের খেলা হবে ক্যাম্পাসে, দশমিকের পরে কত ঘর লিখতে পারো,দেখিয়ে দাও তোমার দক্ষতা। সময় থাকবে মাত্র ১ মিনিট। ১মিনিটে তুমি কয়টা লিখছো পাই এর ডিজিট?" *** রেজিস্টেশন হবে অন স্পট***

AUST Innovation & Design Club has recently organized an online workshop session on ‘Creating Impact on Interview’. The session was conducted through Zoom on 7 August 2020 (Friday). It was about two and a half hours long webinar session and 49 participants had attended the session. Mr. Shakir Hasan was the instructor. He is currently the HR head (Technical Operations) of Novartis Bangladesh Limited.   The main purpose and goal of this workshop were how a fresh graduate or even a running student can handle the interview board. Interview courtesy and manner, what to do and what not to do, and how a person can make himself confident for facing an interview were explained briefly with example.   It was a very valuable session for all the participants. We hope that all the participants can achieve the main purpose of this session and utilize that in their professional life.  #AUST #AUSTIDC #WhereMindsCollide

Aust Innovation and Design Club organised a two-and-a-half hours long workshop on Version Control System with Git & Github. AustIDC held the session online using Zoom on July 5, 2020. The workshop focused on introducing Git and Github to the enthusiasts willing to contribute to an open platform.  Mr Md. Atique Ahmed Ziad, a Front End Developer at Motif and also the GSoC 2020 at Mozilla, conducted these sessions.  The instructor designed the workshop to be task-based for which it was comparatively harder for the participants. But he provided the necessary handouts and instructions aptly so the participants will benefit from them in the future. Many of the participants faced problems with codes, but the instructor was adept to solving those skillfully. The workshop ended with the instructor handing out some exercises to the participants, and he also provided gifts for those who yielded an appropriate solution. Ten participants were able to complete all the provided tasks and will receive a certificate for their participation in this workshop from AustIDC. Overall, the workshop was interactive and well-designed to deliver the basics of Git and Github to enthusiastic participants. AustIDC is grateful to the honourable instructor for providing the time and effort for an active and structured workshop.  #AUST #GitandGitHub #AUSTIDC #WhereMindsCollide

AUST Innovation and Design Club organised a two-day long workshop on Beginners Guide to Machine Learning. AUST IDC held the session online using Zoom on July 1-2, 2020. The workshop focused on introducing Machine Learning to those who have a basic understanding of Python programming. Thirty participants passed a qualifying test and received the chance of participating in this workshop.  Misbah Ull Islam, a Research Assistant of Headblocks and also the Former Chair of IEEE SPS and IEEE ComSoc Joint Student Branch Chapter of Ahsanullah University of Science and Technology, conducted these sessions.  The instructor started off the session with a glimpse of Artificial Intelligence and the uses of Machine Learning in different sectors. He designed this workshop to teach the participants how to make a web application using deep learning. In the first session of this two-day workshop, the instructor mainly discussed the root levels of Machine Learning and using this to build other projects. The participants learned about Linear Regression and its uses in Estimation on Day-1.  Day-2 was all about Classification Analysis, Logistic Regression and OCR. The workshop ended with a Q/A session, where the participants had their queries solved, and the instructor showed them the possible ways the participants can improve what they had learned from this workshop. He had also given a task, upon the completion of which, AustIDC will provide a Certificate to the participants.  Overall, the workshop was interactive and well-designed to deliver the basics of Machine Learning to enthusiastic participants. AUST IDC is grateful to the honourable instructor for providing the time and effort for this practical, yet exciting workshop.  #AUSTIDC #AUST #IDC #MachineLearning #WhereMindsCollide

A two hour long online session was organized by AUST Innovation and Design Club, on CV writing. The workshop was held on ZOOM on June 1, 2020. It started at 8:00 PM with 57 participants.  The session was conducted by Md. Saifur Rahman, Supply Chain-Projects, Beximco Pharmaceuticals Limited.   The session started off as the speaker spoke about on how to write a CV. He shared some valuable insights of an HR about what they expect to see on a CV. He walked us through each part and described about its content in details. Apart from sharing his knowledge, he also reviewed CVs from the participants and pointing out the positives and negatives. The session concluded with a Question and Answer session.   We are incredibly grateful towards Md. Saifur Rahman for conducting such an engrossing and savory workshop. This workshop provided us with better cognizance and will definitely aid us in preparing an impressive CV.

On 24th May 2017, exactly 3 years ago, the journey of AUST Innovation and Design Club had initiated. The day marked a beginning in AUST history as it created an opportunity for the innovators of this university to share their ideas.   AUST Innovation & Design Club, commonly known as AUST IDC is the first ever Tech-Biz club established in Ahsanullah University of Science & Technology. The first inauguration ceremony took place on that day. Since spring 2017, it has been considered as the biggest and most impactful students’ club in the university arena. The Club has no departmental barrier or restriction. AUST IDC has always focused on quality building rather than increasing the numbers only. Yet, within 3 years of struggling, IDC has organized 45+ events which include Technical Workshop, Skill Development Training Program, Informative Seminar, Intra-AUST Students’ Contests, Inter-University Competitions and many more while engaging the prominent industries and multi-national companies as valuable partners into these all!  We are ever grateful to our respected alumni and founding members for creating this club for the students of AUST to bring their ideas into existence, as the motto of the club states "Ideation Into Existence".   Here are some photos to cherish the memories of the special day.

On 12 January 2020, the World Health Organization (WHO) reported that a novel coronavirus was the causing respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City. The virus is so contagious that it reached almost every corner of this planet and brought the whole world to a dead stop within in a matter of month.   The doctors are working under ginormous stress and looking after the affected people. In some occasions, doctors themselves are getting infected due to lack of adequate equipment. If the number of cases proliferates, the hospitals will be forced to turn away patients. The most adverse thing we can do right now is get ourselves infected. We can follow these few simple steps to prevent the virus from spreading:   - Avoid handshakes.  -Wash your hands with soap or alcohol-based hand rub for at least 20 seconds regularly. This kills viruses that may be in your hands. - Wear a mask and gloves when you are going outside. - Avoid crowdy places and maintain at least 1 metre distance between yourself and any other individual. If an infected person coughs or sneezes, they spray droplets containing the virus which you might breath in. - Isolate yourself if you have the slightest symptom of COVID-19.  #StayHome #StaySafe

To enlighten the visual representation and analysis of data using the Microsoft Excel, AUST Innovation and Design Club (AUST IDC) organized a 2-hours long workshop entitled “Workshop On Data Visualization & Analysis using Excel”, in collaboration with Teach For Bangladesh (TFB).   The workshop took place on February 20, 2021 (Saturday) from 7.00 PM to 9.00 PM. The session was streamed via Zoom toward 80 selected participants, who registered free for this event beforehand.  Mr. Mrinmoy Sarker, currently serving the Teach For Bangladesh (TFB) as Deputy Manager of Fellowship Recruitment & Selection, conducted the workshop. He accomplished his Master's in Educational Leadership & School Development from BRAC University and pursued B.Tech. in Electrical Engineering at National Institute of Technology - NIT Durgapur, India.   The Workshop was designed to explore the depths of Excel in this age of Big Data, it’s utilization and analyzing data to visually construct a content that both technical and non-technical people can recognize. In this workshop, the participants were provided a clear hands-on experience about the data analysis tools related, but not limited to, the graphical representation of unassembled data. During the workshop the participants explored a range of techniques that they can utilize to increase revenues, cut costs, improve customer relationships, reduce risks and more. The knowledge they gathered from this workshop would help them to make their relevant activities easier.   The session started through a welcoming speech from Ms. Ishrakul Munzerin, General Secretary of AUST Innovation & Design Club. After a brief introduction of the speaker, the session started.  Mr. Mrinmoy Sarker commenced the workshop with an ice-breaking session by interacting with the participants and providing them valuable counsel on the applications of Excel in the job industry. The workshop was task-based and the instructor aptly directed the session so the participants were able to learn the tool for Data Analysis, Visual Representation of Data and Information Management.  In the later portion, Mr. Sarker handed out some exercises to the participants for practicing and presented an extensive overview of Teach For Bangladesh (TFB), its goal, mission and vision. The participants were inspired to take a deeper look into the fight against the education inequality in Bangladesh.   Mr. Abdur Rahman Showrov, Joint Secretary of AUST IDC and Ambassador of Teach For Bangladesh concluded the event with a short speech keeping the hope of having more collaborations in future.  Overall, the workshop was interactive and well-designed to meet the demand of students accurately. AUST Innovation and Design Club is grateful to Teach For Bangladesh. The Club expresses its gratitude to the honorable instructor for his precious time and effort to conduct such a well-structured training session.

On the 30th January of 2021, AUST Innovation and Design Club organized a two hours long Hands-on Workshop on Game Development using Unity. The session was held using Zoom, from 7 PM to 9 PM (Bangladesh Std. Time). Almost 100 participants were given the opportunity to join the session due to slot constraints, altho the number of registrations were double in number.   The session delved into the endless possibilities of Game Development and how to get started with it. The session was designed to give the participants a clear idea about Unity and Game development methodologies.  Mr. Shamit Ahmed, instructed the workshop. He is currently a Game developer at Free Pixel Games. He graduated from AUST, CSE Department (35th Batch). He also served as Joint-Secretary of AUST Innovation & Design Club.  The event created a lot of buzz among the students. Nearly 200 Students registered, however we only had 100 seat slots. Therefore, only 100 participants were allowed to attend the event, prioritizing the students of CSE department. Only 41% of the total applicants were allowed to join the event among total registrations.

Important Notice: Candidates who get selected for any workshop this semester, but fail to join the event will be blacklisted.  Blacklisted candidates will not be allowed to participate in any other AUST IDC events of Spring'20 semester.   Selected candidates for the "Game Development using Unity" workshop will be emailed tonight with all necessary software installation instructions via email.

AUST Innovation and Design Club organized two hours long online session entitled “3D Printing 101: Peeking into the World of 3D Printing”. The session was held using Zoom on the 2nd, 2021(Saturday) from 7 PM to 9 PM (Bangladesh Std. Time). The session delved into the endless possibilities that Additive manufacturing offers and the revolutionary change in the existing industries.   The session was designed to give the participants a clear idea about the 3D printing technology and its dramatic influence which eventually will guide newcomers to learn about the current industry and dive into the endless possibilities of additive manufacturing.   Mr. Arafat Mohiv Munna, the CEO of “3D Printing Hub” and the only current student of AUST in possession of “Certified Solidworks Associate” certification conducted the session. He shared his experiences of countless collaborations with renowned companies regarding 3D printing services.   The event created a lot of buzz among the students of AUST and it was evident with a massive 5.1k people reach throughout different online mediums and recorded 80+ registration responses. Around half of the students who registered were invited to participate in this session. The session was successfully managed by AUST Innovation and Design Club Committee members and the participants were able to gather a plethora of knowledge.
